    {
      "text": "Following is the correct sequence of steps in PCR",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Denaturation \u2192 Construction \u2192 Extension \u2192 Annealing",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Construction \u2192 Denaturation \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Extension",
          "correct": true
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Construction \u2192 Extension \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Denaturation",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Extension \u2192 Construction \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Denaturation",
          "correct": false
        }
      ],
      "correct_answer": "B. Construction \u2192 Denaturation \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Extension",
      "question_images": [],
      "explanation_images": [],
      "explanation": "<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>\u2022 Denaturation (94\u201398\u00b0C) \u2013 The double-stranded DNA is heated to a high temperature to break the hydrogen bonds between the complementary strands, resulting in single-stranded DNA templates for the next step.</li><li>\u2022 Annealing (50\u201365\u00b0C) \u2013 The reaction mixture is cooled to allow primers to bind (anneal) to their complementary sequences on the single-stranded DNA. The exact temperature depends on the melting temperature (Tm) of the primers.</li><li>\u2022 Extension (72\u00b0C) \u2013 DNA polymerase (usually Taq polymerase) synthesizes the new DNA strand by adding dNTPs complementary to the template strand. This step occurs at the enzyme\u2019s optimal temperature, ensuring efficient DNA elongation.</li><li>\u2022 Incorrect Options: (A) Denaturation \u2192 Construction \u2192 Extension \u2192 Annealing \u2013 Incorrect because the reaction setup (construction) occurs before the thermal cycling. Additionally, annealing should occur before extension to allow primers to bind to the template DNA.</li><li>\u2022 (C) Construction \u2192 Extension \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Denaturation \u2013 Incorrect because extension cannot occur before primer annealing or DNA denaturation. The single-stranded template must first be available for primer binding and polymerase activity.</li><li>\u2022 (D) Extension \u2192 Construction \u2192 Annealing \u2192 Denaturation \u2013 Incorrect because the reaction setup happens before any thermal cycling. Also, extension cannot precede denaturation and annealing, as these steps are necessary for primer binding and DNA polymerase function.</li></ul>\n<p></p>",
