      "explanation": "<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>\u2022 (B) Mutations \u2013 Mutations refer to any permanent changes in the DNA sequence, including point mutations, insertions, and deletions. While all SNPs are mutations, not all mutations are SNPs. SNPs are defined by their common occurrence in the population (<1% frequency), whereas most mutations are rarer and can be harmful or neutral.</li><li>\u2022 (C) Transposons \u2013 Transposons, or \"jumping genes,\" are DNA sequences that can move within the genome. While they contribute to genetic variation and evolution, they are not as frequent as SNPs in terms of small-scale sequence variations.</li></ul>\n<p></p>",
