      "explanation": "<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>\u2022 (C) PCR with allele-specific oligonucleotide hybridization \u2013 This method is highly effective for detecting point mutations. PCR amplifies the beta-globin gene region, and allele-specific oligonucleotide (ASO) probes are used to hybridize specifically to either the normal or mutant sequence. This enables differentiation between normal, carrier (heterozygous), and affected (homozygous mutant) individuals.</li><li>\u2022 (D) DNA sequencing \u2013 DNA sequencing is the most definitive method for detecting point mutations. By directly reading the nucleotide sequence of the beta-globin gene, sequencing precisely identifies the sickle cell mutation (A \u2192T transversion at codon 6). It is widely used in genetic diagnosis and research.</li></ul>\n<p></p>",
